[1] Philippines (Zambo)
Date: Wed 1 Jun 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org> & A-lan Banks
<A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Balita Organization, Philippines, 1 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://news.balita.ph/html/public_html/article.php?story=20050601194928276>

Dengue outbreak alarms Zambo officials
-----------------------------------------------
Despite the city government's continuing anti-dengue campaign, the number
of cases continues to increase, and health officials are alarmed that the
number of dengue fever cases is already reaching "outbreak" proportions.
City Health Officer Rodel Agbulos said on Monday [30 May 2005] that 289
dengue cases were registered in his office between January and 1 May 2005,
up from 40 cases over the same period last year. It was an increase of 298
percent.
Agbulos said the places that have a high number of dengue cases this year
[2005] are the health districts of Santa Maria, Baliwasan and Sangali.
He met on Monday [30 May 2005] with the dengue-control team to come up with
measures to contain the problem, and he sought the help of concerned
government agencies to curb the incidence of the disease.
Agbulos would also re-activate the barangay dengue brigade to intensify the
anti-dengue campaign.
According to Medicine Net.com, the website of the US Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, dengue fever is an acute viral infection caused by
a bite from the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. The primary form of dengue fever
is characterized by a skin rash and a high fever with severe headache and
muscle pain. Other symptoms may include chills, diarrhea and vomiting.
Bouts of extreme exhaustion may last for months after the initial symptoms.
The Department of Health reports thousands of dengue cases each year. In
June last year [2004], the health department reported that a total of 2332
dengue cases were admitted to sentinel hospitals nationwide from 1 Jan to
15 May 2004, with 16 deaths.
The DOH National Epidemiology Center (NEC) reported a 58 percent decrease
in the number of cases this year [2005] compared with the same period in 2003.
According to the NEC's mid-year report last year [2004], the regions with
the highest number of cases were Metro Manila, Central Luzon, Bicol and
Eastern Visayas. The ages of cases ranged from one month to 75 years old,
with 46 percent (535) of the cases belonging to the one-year-to-9-years age
group.
Health officials usually note an increase in dengue cases during the rainy
season, and the DOH repeatedly warns the public to bring a suspected dengue
case to the nearest hospital for early diagnosis.
--
