[2]
Date 2 Jun 2005
From: A-lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com> & Mary Marshall
<<tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Alert Net UK
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/BKK53537.htm>
Thailand warns of more major dengue outbreaks
----------------------------
Thailand said on Thursday it feared more major outbreaks of dengue fever, a
sometimes fatal disease with so far has killed 16 people this year.
In tropical Thailand, where mosquitoes are a familiar pest in every home,
dengue has so far infected 10 390 people this year, of whom 16 have died.
It infected 2687 people during the week of 22-28 May [2005] alone, of whom
2 died, the Health Ministry said.
"Dengue fever this year has a tendency to be more severe than last year,
possibly because of the cycle of the outbreaks, erupting every 2 years, is
reaching its peak this year," Health Minister Suchai Charoenrattanakul said
in a statement.
"As Thailand is now in the rainy season, we would like to urge all 12
million households to be careful."
The mosquito-born disease, for which there is no vaccine and no specific
treatment, killed 176 of 114 800 infected people in 2002.
Symptoms include high fever, severe headaches, backache, joint pain, nausea
and vomiting, eye pain and rashes.
--
